The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly unleashed an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups and advocate that the government can use the small boxes to record the miles they were driven – and possibly where they were driven – and then use the information to calculate tax rulings.
The tea party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of data protection concerns.
But while one cannot agree on a move in Congress, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently examining how they can switch to a system where drivers pay per mile driven over the next ten years.
Thousands of drivers have already tested the drivers, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is really a must for our country.
“It’s nothing we’ll only be able to use,” said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of Southern California’s Assn. of Governments, who plans to record the mileage of all California drivers in the state from 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is funded from taxes, is struggling to pay Americans at the threshold.
But in America, there is no longer as much tanking as before.
Cars consume less fuel.
