“This is the most meaningful alternative in the long term,” he said.
Bureaucrats refer to it as a mileage-based user fee.
It’s no surprise that the idea comes up in urban liberals, because the tax could, for example, be used to influence driving behaviour in a way that reduces congestion and climate-damaging exhaust gases.
The California planners focus on the system in the development of strategies to achieve the state’s ambitious, legally anchored climate change goals.
But Pennsylvania Republican Bill Shuster, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees the most common long-term alternative in it.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation have also come up with the idea of letting drivers pay for the route back.
“This is not a tax that disappears in a black hole,” says Adrian Moore, vice president of policy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former U.S. transport ministers, who in a 2011 report called on Congress to move towards mileage-based billing.
Last year, the U.S. Senate approved a $90 million pilot project that would have included 10,000 cars.
However, the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the advance and thus responded to the concerns of MPs from rural areas who represent people who often have to travel many miles on their way to work or to the city in everyday life.
Several states and major cities still do not move on their own in this direction.
The most engaged is Oregon, which currently recruits 5,000 drivers for the country’s largest experiment.
