New York City is also considering such a thing.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, to which the transport ministries of 17 states on the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida) are now investigating how to implement the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the devices, motorists were skeptical that the government could track any of their movements.
“Thinking about Big Brother and stuff like that was a big problem,” said Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and results management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want it.
Following the test, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: “It would be relatively easy to turn the drivers into adult surveillance devices.”
There is no need to build a gigantic, cumbersome technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to capture data about the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that allows the state to capture the miles driven, but not exactly when and where.
So, according to Khan, the public would also be more calm.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The company was not originally set up to help federal states in taxing motorists.
Rather, their goal was to set foot in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers are to pay based on the miles driven.
But the devices they test are also interesting for road planners, because they do not work with GPS and only provide limited information that is regularly uploaded via modem.
