Other agencies hope to be able to sell the concept to a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more features than with fewer.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a taxing device that also allows parking fees to be paid, insurance only has to be paid for miles driven and speed data collected from other vehicles in real time, thanks to which drivers can avoid traffic jams.
“Car drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits that the system offers,” says a planning document from the city.
However, some traffic planners wonder if the whole thing about paying per mile is not just a huge distraction maneuver.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials said Congress could easily solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund by raising fuel taxes.
