Esa Decides on Big Space Missions: Missions for Billions
Remote planets, gravitational waves or black holes - experts from the European Space Agency must now agree on two major projects that they want to launch in the coming years.
30 proposals were to be selected, five are still in the race.
distant worlds.
More than 1,000 planets with other stars have already been found by astronomers.
Whether there is life on at least some of them, no one knows.
The choice is difficult: should one look for gravitational waves?
Or would you rather explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or hunt for Earth-like planets and thus perhaps discover extraterrestrial life?
These are the questions posed by the European Space Agency (ESA).
For their "Cosmic Vision" program, they are looking for ideas for two major space projects that are designed to advance research decisively.
The state for such "L-missions" in each case amounts to approximately one billion euros.
The launch is expected to be in 2028 and 2034.
In early September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
30 Ideas were debated, five of them have now come to the narrower choice.
Numerous bodies reviewed the proposals, hooking up with the researchers.
In the coming days, a final decision will be taken by the Scientific Programme Committee.
A total of four major questions have been selected by the ESA, to which the missions of the 2007 initiated program "Cosmic Vision" should find answers.
What are the conditions for the formation of planets and life?
The exact processes in the formation of stars from large gas clouds – and thus the formation of planets orbiting these stars – are still in the verbal darkness.
A large infrared telescope in the universe could penetrate this darkness.
And if a star has a planet, under what circumstances can life arise there?
To address this question, the space telescope “Cheops” is set to launch in 2017, with which 500 already-known planetary systems in our immediate vicinity will be explored in more detail.
However, the possibilities are limited, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, astronomers could image Earth-like planets and even analyze the composition of their atmospheres and thus search for "biomarkers": gases that are considered an index of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
Finally, this question should also provide an explanation as to what conditions there are for the creation of life.
An important role is played by the magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field as well as the particle radiation emanating from it with the planetary system.
In our solar system, these processes can be studied by way of example.
With the "Solar Orbiter", the Esa has already approved a M-class mission (that is where the budget is about half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is scheduled to launch in 2017 and accurately observe the sun’s surface and activity.
Jupiter and its moon are also of great interest to the researchers.
They want to find out what role the giant planet has played in the development of the solar system.
For this purpose, the ESA plans the first of three L-missions of the "Cosmic Vision" program.
The probe "Juice" (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and is to explore the atmosphere of the planet as well as the icy moons Europa, Kallisto and Ganymede.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
The space offers many opportunities to study matter under extreme conditions and thus to investigate whether the laws of nature we know are still valid there.
There may also be discrepancies that could lead physicists to a new theory under whose roof all known laws of nature can be united.
How did the universe come into being and where does it come from?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the hurricane.
In addition to the matter we are familiar with, from the stars, planets, and beings like us, there is dark matter, whose gravity holds galaxies and clusters of galaxies together, and dark energy, through which the expansion of the universe accelerates.
So far, the researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first fractions of seconds of the hurricane, nor what dark matter and dark energy consist of.
With "Euclid", the Esa has already approved an M-Mission here, which is scheduled to launch in 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe is to study the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time in the entire sky, thus enabling conclusions on the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could do the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will remain at the end of the selection process.
According to many experts, the best chances for approval as an L-Mission has "E-Lisa", a sophisticated concept for detecting gravitational waves.
Physicists understand changes in the structure of space-time that Albert Einstein predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been proven to date.
Elisa could do that, the scientists hope, behind the project.
The mission includes a detector consisting of two or three probes, which is stationed in space.
It could also prove gravitational waves, as opposed to Earth’s facilities, that were created at the time of the crash, and thus provide new insights into the origin of the cosmos.
Four more proposals are still competing for the second L-mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena", which is to explore black holes, among other things, "Icy Planets", another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism", a mission to measure the cosmic background, and "Ex" on the surface of the planet.
