An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient history.
Why should one expect an independent Scotland to dance after the European pipe?
Why does the London Joc trade against that of Brussels, especially now?
These are the real European news: the great post-war plan for the unification of Europe has come to an end.
With the euro crisis, the project Europe has officially died.
All over the EU, parties who are hostile to the EU gain ground or want to throw the euro on board as a common currency.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative Party for Germany – founded only this year – managed to win almost five million votes in the September federal election, effectively driving the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic resistance to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
However, the current economic crisis is a turning point.
Due to the strict austerity policy imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in connection with the forced jacket in which the respective national economy is needed by holding on to the common currency, many people believe that the project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments causing excessive budget deficits – this was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has pinned its members to exchange rates that are beneficial to German exporters – and German politicians would like to do so.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the local currency, Southern Europe will find itself with a built-in productivity downturn compared to Germany.
The only way is to reduce wages and public spending – spurred by Berlin.
Behind the current state and currency problems lies a deepening European productivity problem.
As a result of the “green” energy directives mandated by Brussels – a code for subsidizing French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers – European industry pays double for electricity and quadruple for gas compared to the United States.
This is a palpable cost downside, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
All the world’s payroll records do not protect the European petrochemical industry from being pushed into the corner by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is taking place, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, France’s political elite saw the EU as a vehicle to keep Germany in check and raise Paris to the eye with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimation and Europe has pushed its own economic policy, which has the French economy to fight.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s right-wing, EU-hostile Front National has just won a decisive re-election, leading the ruling socialists to third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote – a timely warning for the British Labour Party that it cannot assume a split in the right spectrum would automatically mean benefits for the left.
What does Le Pen do with its newly gained popularity among the white working class French?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-Community currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties cut off well in these elections – and this is very well possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point I want to go beyond: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the common currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become more like the “Europe of the (sovereign) nations” that General de Gaulle favored.
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may hold onto the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect the United Kingdom to distance itself from this project in the hope of getting involved with the United States.
However, Washington’s growing interest in the Pacific region suggests that Britain will stand alone in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland in all of this?
We can decide to be a region of (last resort) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – which also includes telling Berlin and Brussels what they can get where.
I suspect that Scotland could do very well in a looser European union if we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other similar thinking countries is easier in an unfederated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same to Norway and maintaining our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and has won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and committed) cuts made by Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to choose independence now, only to be forced to have a austerity policy from Berlin and Brussels.
