The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain the genetic information for the production of nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
Antibodies hunt down the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, thereby preventing a smoker from experiencing nicotine-high.
In trials, vaccinated mice who were given nicotine retained their normal level of activity.
Mice without vaccination, on the other hand, would have taken a "delay", the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine has reached their brain.
