FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices in airplanes (but do not conduct cell phone conversations)
Air travelers can now use their electronic devices from departure to landing to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies, but not phone, according to the new guidelines issued on Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the United States.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented depends on the respective airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
The airlines must prove to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the training manuals of flight personnel as well as the regulations for stowing the equipment in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it has already received plans from some airlines that want to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
“Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve the extended use of electronic devices very soon,” the FAA said in a statement.
Passengers are currently required to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They are only allowed to restart them once the aircraft has reached a height of three kilometers and gives the captain green light.
Upon entry into the landing, the passengers must turn them off again and must not restart before the aircraft has landed.
According to the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are protected from electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices even when starting, landing and on the runway, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft that have been refitted for the use of Wi-Fi at higher altitudes should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Professional Aviation Association, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is implemented safely – and we work closely with the airline in this regard – both sides will benefit from it,” Glading said.
We are truly sorry to have to feel like a caretaker on this issue.
Nevertheless, internet connections to surf, exchange e-mails, text messages or download data below three kilometers remained prohibited, the authority explained.
Passengers are asked to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So still no "Words With Friends", the Scrabble-like online game played by actor Alec Baldwin on his smartphone in 2011 when he had to leave a public jet of American Airlines because he refused to turn off the device while the plane was parked on the flight deck.
And heavier devices such as laptops must also continue to be stowed away, as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin.
Cell phone calls during the flight are also still prohibited.
The regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices when starting and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the Transportation Safety Authority National Transportation Safety Board, security experts for national traffic issues on CBS News, said mobile phones would still be considered a risk.
“Handy is really a problem, not just because it could potentially cause malfunctions in navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that transmission from the air can also disrupt transmission masts,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee, which was launched by the FAA to investigate this issue, last month recommended that the government allow a broader use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure on the FAA has increased to loosen restrictions on use.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri are of the opinion that there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce, because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
In some studies, it is said that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore switching off the device.
The FAA began to restrict the use of electronic devices by air passengers in 1966, after reports of malfunctions of navigation and communication devices by passenger-guided UKW radios that were the latest technology trend at the time.
New aircraft are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also so designed and approved by the FAA that electronic interference does not matter to them.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi for several years when the flight altitude is reached.
The flyers adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also more insensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for the stronger use of electronic devices according to the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today’s electronic devices generally emit significantly less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, only emit minimal radiation when you flip over.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
One of the advocates of loosening restrictions on the use of devices by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees invited a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and made a test flight to determine problems, but could not detect them.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using devices.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believes the disruption to the devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members said there are only isolated reports of pilots speaking out for a malfunction of aircraft systems through the devices, and most of them are very old.
The FAA recommended, however, that pilots be allowed to order the switching off of the devices by the passengers when the instrument lands under poor visibility conditions.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a reasonable adjustment for travelers who today would be equipped with extensive technology.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not at odds with safety,” said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
