Hearing before the Royal Commission: Two YMCA employees charged with sexual assault charges against Jonathan Lord
Two YMCA employees from New South Wales (NSW) have been charged with child-related sexual offences before allegations against childcare worker Jonathan Lord of Caringbah were raised in 2011, as the Royal Commission on Child Sexual Abuse learned.
However, in the opening statement before the Commission, the YMCA had stated that “the organization has never had anything to do with an incident of sexual abuse of children”.
Managing Director Phillip Hare was questioned about one case in which one YMCA employee had been charged with child pornography offences, and another in which a YMCA sports teacher at Caringbah Hall had been convicted of child abuse in 1991.
Hare told Gail Furness, one of the Commission’s assistant lawyers that he knew about the first case, but did not know the second.
He admitted that the YMCA’s opening statement to the Commission was also inaccurate in the claim that “there have been external reviews of the YMCA in which the YMCA has been recognised as at the forefront of child safety”.
Evidence before the Commission shows that the YMCA was informed that it received the second-lowest rating of four possible in a quality audit by the Department of Education and Communities in August of the year.
Hare, who started at 21 at the YMCA, admitted that the management had “failed from me down” at Lord’s appointment and did not ensure that employees were aware of their obligations to report violations of the child safety guidelines.
At the beginning of the year, Lord was convicted of sexual misconduct against twelve boys during his two-year tenure with the YMCA.
He was sentenced to at least six years in prison.
Hare argues, however, that the YMCA would have a cultural problem that prevented employees from reporting Lord’s violations regarding children’s safety.
The staff said they had observed violations, including that Lord was alone with children, cared for them privately as a babysitter, let them sit on his lap, told one that he loved it, and let children play with his phone.
Danielle Ockwell, whose supervisor was Lord and who had asked for a training for child protection because she was worried about his behavior, said that the child services manager Jacqui Barnat, who was Lords' supervisor at YMCA Caringbah, was "very intimidating and most of the time very near".
The Managing Director stated that he would not accept statements from employees, which they would not have trusted to reimburse their superiors.
Rather, he said, their friendship with the Lord had impaired their judgment, which is why they had not reported him.
Hare stated that he informed the YMCA NSW Board of Directors that the lesson that the organization had to draw from the “Jonathan-Lord incident” was “not about reporting” by employees, and the Board agreed to it.
Hare said the decision to push employees to sign confidentiality obligations shortly after the charges were filed had been made by YMCA’s child services chief Liam Whitley.
He said that contamination of the evidence should be prevented, but that was “overt” and poorly implemented.
The YMCA NSW was not a safe organization for children at the time Jonathan Lord was employed there between 2009 and 2011, said Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University, an expert on sexual abuse of children, the Commission.
He explained that there were “serious problems” in hiring, checking, hiring, training and supervising employees.
The hearing was postponed until December 20.
