Scientists have been able to shed more light on the context in which a dog’s squealing is related to its mood.
Previous research has shown that happy dogs with their tail velt more to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while in nervous dogs it was the left side.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive these subtle differences and respond to them.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, said: “It is well known in humans that the left and right half of the brain respond differently to stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions.”
Here we have tried to look at this with other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just like in humans, the right half of the brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in the emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the lateral swans of their fellow species, the researchers monitor the animals as these films look at other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four legs and analyzed the behavior.
We’ll probably soon understand why the cock is moving in one direction or the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed the dogs films with dogs – either a natural-looking version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw how an otherwise expressionless dog moved the tail to the right (from the perspective of the wandering dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail tends mainly to the left (again from the dog’s point of view, which wags), then their heart rate increased and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs would have learned from experience, what movements they should worry about and when not.
He said: “If you have different encounters with other dogs and the sneezing with the tail is linked in a direction rather with friendly behavior and the right side produces a less friendly behavior, then you react based on these experiences.”
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians, and trainers better understand their animal’s emotions.
John Bradshaw, an expert on dog behavior and guest scholarship at the University of Bristol’s Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, said this was not the first study to investigate whether left and right are important for dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads left when they look at an aggressive dog, and right when it comes to a satisfied dog.
In another research paper at the University of Victoria in Canada, “dogs are more likely to approach a robot dog if its ‘tail’ rolls to the left and not to the right, rather than getting restless – just differently than in the Italian study.”
According to his statement, the differences could therefore stir that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could help, he explained.
“While there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two halves of the brain are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined – and dogs are no exception,” Bradshaw said.
