Nathaniel P. Morris is a second year student at Harvard Medical School.
I am currently reading a very sad book.
It’s a book that I believed would cheer me up during my thirty-second year of medical school and give me hope again.
It is called "The Audacity to Win" and describes Barack Obama's memoirs for the 2008 presidential election.
When I finish my patient records in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and a speech could take my breath away.
The election was a landslide victory and news reporters held in order to keep an eye on the historical significance of this hour.
My classmates were crying with joy and my parents were collecting all the papers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on their way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama took office in 2008, he had approval ratings of 82%.
And then I close the book.
Switching back to the present is a bad awakening, as if you are being torn from a dream.
It’s hard to remember these optimistic times – they seem to be a vague memory, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first cast my vote, something has actually changed.
But it's just not something I could have imagined.
I recognize the great and versatile things Obama has achieved, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act for Health Insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of the enforced silence of homosexuality in the army and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I am also of the opinion that party-political blockade tactics have tipped off too many efforts with which our nation should be brought forward: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance and the closure of Guantanamo Bay, to name just a few.
But after defending the Obama administration against colleagues and acquaintances countless times, I have come to an end with my attempts at explanation.
I have reached a point of political desperation.
The republican blockade policy cannot explain why it allows the interrogation of foreign heads of state or the killing of innocent children by drones overseas.
It cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data about the private lives of Americans and why whistleblowers are being punished that expose state misconduct.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, a U.S. citizen, was murdered without trial, nor why public funding and spending limits are being bypassed during the presidential elections.
It does not justify the results of a report stating that the White House’s efforts to calm the media are the “most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.”
And most recently, it cannot excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the adoption of the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if that's what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood at 18 that government work could be contrary to its previous political campaigns.
Obviously, the House of Representatives is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and random events such as the Newtown massacre shape the public discussion.
But when I look at the examples above, they seem to be largely elected by the government itself.
And that bothers me the most.
I re-elected Obama in 2012, not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was a confusing and inexhaustible alternative, he seemed unable to determine his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of future elections, would fulfill the hope we had heard of for so long.
But with Obama’s approval ratings down to less than 45% this week, the return to 2008 has become so tougher with this book.
