Travelling through mud, rivers and jungles for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle brings free medical care to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
In the West African country there are not many doctors, only one for 5,000 people.
Match here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 CNN Heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other heroes in the top 10 to choose him as the "CNN Hero of the Year".
The winner receives $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched as his sick father repeatedly lost consciousness and traveled to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first he had only one broken arm, but then an inflammation formed that spread to his brain and there caused a haematoma that was supposed to affect him for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have brought him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father in overcrowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
“It’s not easy,” Bwelle comments.
You can leave the house at five in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and yet not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwell’s father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organization.
In contrast, the ratio in the United States is for a doctor for 413 people.
But even if there was a doctor for them, most Cameroonians could not afford to visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and nearly three-quarters of health spending in the country is private.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
His father and so many of his countrymen suffered in Bwelle made the decision to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team conducted 700 free surgeries last year.
He became a doctor himself and worked as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
In addition, he founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and offers free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday he and up to 30 people force themselves in minibuses and ride on the roof with the cordoned medical equipment over unmounted terrain to the villages that need help.
Not always everything goes smoothly.
More than once, they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they will be welcomed as heroes: a party, singing and dancing and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and bee – with its broad smile and its boundless energy – is happy to be with the celebration.
The next morning, the team starts with the examination of hundreds of patients.
“We treat 500 people per ride,” says Bwelle.
They come from a circle of 60 kilometers around the village – and that on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crucifixes, donated glasses, or free birth certificates – a document required for school, but many poor families simply can’t afford it.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The surgeries usually take place in a school, town hall or apartment; after the procedure, the patients get up and go to the recreation area to make room for the next one.
The lighting for the OP and the disinfection equipment is fed by the generator of the group and so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of the morning on Sunday.
It’s an exhausting mindset, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
“They’re drumming all night so we can stay awake and continue our work,” says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team then drives back to the city, tired but proud of the work done.
The group – a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – has carried out 700 free surgeries in the past year and knows that with its work, it makes a huge difference to the people it helps.
One man explained that the free operation of a break-in he received now enabled him to work again.
“It changes the future of my family,” he said.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at private clinics in Yaoundé at night.
With this second job, he finances 60% of his non-profit activity, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
“I really don’t know when he’s sleeping,” says Katie O’Malley, who studies medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia in her second year and volunteers in Bwell’s group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go to these campaigns.
For medical and health care students like O’Malley, who come from the US and Europe and support bees, this is a chance to gain practical experiences they would never get at home.
“We can be involved in surgeries where we help drop blood or hold the instruments for Dr. Bwelle,” O’Malley explains.
This would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
Students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and often bring donated medical supplies with them.
But if she is first in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, transport and guidance.
“He’s a hero without a doubt,” O’Malley said.
He dedicates his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no boundaries.
For bee, almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live a happier life, and thereby fulfilling a promise he made to his father, brings him great joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this job,” Bwelle says.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
